@Node "Save"
Clicking over this gadget will create (or update) a file named SCOPTIONS
in the current directory.
@EndNode

@Node "Save Default"
Clicking over this gadget will create (or update) a global SCOPTIONS file,
which resides in the ENV:SC directory.
@EndNode

@Node "Cancel"
Clicking over this gadget will cancel any changes made, and will exit the
SCOPTS program without modifying any files.
@EndNode

@Node "SPECIAL"
This string gadget may be used for any option not directly supported
through gadgets in the SCOPTS program.
@EndNode

@Node "OK"
Accept changes on this subpanel and return to Main panel.
@EndNode

@Node "User"
This string gadget is used to enter the name of a user-created startup
file.  This gadget is only active if @{" STARTUP " Link "STARTUP"}=<user>.
@EndNode

@Node "AbsFuncPointer"
AFP=AbsFuncPointer/S			Default: noafp

Description

   generates 32-bit references to functions when loading function
   pointers.  If you specify noabsfuncpointer and you take the address of
   a function that is more than 32k away, the linker generates an ALV
   (automatic link vector) jump instruction that allows your code to work.
   However, if you compare the address of the function to a function
   pointer assigned elsewhere, you may get a different value.  Specify
   absfuncpointer if your code is larger than 64K or in multiple code
   hunks and you compare function pointers.  Specifying absfuncpointer may
   increase the size of your executable.
@EndNode

@Node "ADDSYM"
@Title "ADDSYMbols"
ADDSYM=ADDSYMbols/S			Default: noaddsym

Description

   Tells the linker to add symbol information to the executable module.

   This option is automatically enabled if you specify the @{" DeBuG " Link "DeBuG"} option.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" DeBuG " Link "DeBuG"} , @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "ANSI"
ANSI/S					Default: noansi

Description

   This option enforces the strictest interpretation of the @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} C
   standard.  Using this option produces many additional warning messages.

   To be completely @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"}-compliant (that is, if you require a pure
   @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} namespace), you should also define the preprocessor symbol
   @{" _STRICT_ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/_STRICT_ANSI"} before including any header files.

   If you require support for @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lig.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} trigraphs, specify the  @{" TRIGraph " Link "TRIGraph"}
   option also.

See Also
   @{" ANSI Definition " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} , @{" _STRICT_ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/_STRICT_ANSI"} , @{" TRIGraph " Link "TRIGraph"}
@EndNode

@Node "ARGumentSIZe"
ARGSIZ=ARGumentSIZe/K/N 		Default: 512

Description

   This option sets the size of the maximum argument to a preprocessor
   macro.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   The @{" MEMorySIZE " Link "MEMSIZE"} option sets the ARGumentSIZe (and other internal
   limits) to different default values if you do not specify ARGumentSIZe.

See Also

   @{" MEMorySIZE " Link "MEMSIZE"}
@EndNode

@Node "ASseMbler"
ASM=ASseMbler/K

Description

   This option specifies assembly-language files that are to be assembled
   and, if you specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option, linked into the program.

   This option does not have a negative form.

See Also

   @{" CSouRCe " Link "CSouRCe"} , @{" LIBrary " Link "LIBraries"} , @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" OBJect " Link "OBJects"}
@EndNode

@Node "AUTOREGister"
AUTOREG=AUTOREGister/S			Default: autoreg

Description

   This option enables automatic register selection by the code generator.
   If you specify AUTOREGister, the compiler attempts to add register
   variables to the variables that have already been chosen by the global
   optimizer or declared with the register keyword.
@EndNode

@Node "BATCH"
BATCH/S 				Default: nobatch

Description

   This option tells the linker not to prompt for definitions of undefined
   symbols.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "BSSMEM"
@Title "BSSMEMory"
BSSMEM=BSSMEMory/K			Default: any

Description

   This option specifies the type of memory into which uninitialized
   external data items should be loaded.  You can specify ANY, CHIP, or
   FAST for type.  You can abbreviate these values as A, C, or F.  This
   option does not have a negative form.

   This option affects code generated by both the compiler and the
   assembler.

See also

   @{" CODEMEMory " Link "CODEMEM"} , @{" DATAMEMory " Link "DATAMEM"}
@EndNode

@Node "BSSNAME"
BSSName/K				Default: "udata"

Description

   This option names the uninitialized data section.  You can specify
   BSSNAME=NONE or NOBSSNAME if you want an unnamed BSS section.  The
   linker automatically merges all sections with the same name.

See Also

   @{" CODENAME " Link "CODENAME"} , @{" DATANAME " Link "DATANAME"}
@EndNode

@Node "CODE"
CODE/K					Default: near

Description

   This option specifies whether you want 16-bit or 32-bit references to
   functions not declared in the current file.	You can specify NEAR or
   N for 16-bit references or FAR or F for 32-bit references.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Most programs do not need this option even if they are very large,
   because the linker creates a jump instruction (an ALV) for any
   references to functions that are out of range.

See Also

   @{" DATA " Link "DATA"}
@EndNode

@Node "CODEMEM"
@Title "CODEMEMory"
CODEMEM=CODEMEMory/K			Default: any

Description

   This option specifies the type of memory into which code should be
   loaded.  You can specify ANY, CHIP, or FAST.  You can abbreviate these
   values as A, C, or F.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   This option affects code generated by both the compiler and the
   assembler.

See Also

   @{" BSSMEMory " Link "BSSMEM"} , @{" DATAMEMory " Link "DATAMEM"}
@EndNode

@Node "CODENAME"
CODENAME/K				Default: "text"

Description

   This option names the code section.	You can specify CODENAME=NONE or
   NOCODENAME if you want an unnamed code section.  The linker
   automatically merges all sections with the same name.

See Also

   @{" BSSNAME " Link "BSSNAME"} , @{" DATANAME " Link "DATANAME"}
@EndNode

@Node "CommentNEST"
CNEST=CommentNEST/S			Default: nocnest

Description

   This option allows nested comments.	Nested comments occur when one
   comment is totally contained inside another.  The @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} Standard
   prohibits nested comments, so in @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"}-compliant code, the first
   comment end sequence (*/) terminates both comments.

See Also

   @{" ANSI Definition " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} , @{" ANSI Switch " Link "ANSI"}
@EndNode

@Node "COMMON"
COMMON/S				Default: nocommon

Description

   This option tells the compiler to use the common model for external
   data.  If you specify NOCOMMON, the compiler uses the strict
   reference-definition model.
@EndNode

@Node "CONSTLIBbase"
CONSTLIB=CONSTLIBbase/S 		Default: constlib

Description

   This option tells the compiler that library base pointers are set once
   then remain constant throughout your entire program.  If you change the
   value of your library bases after setting them, you should specify the
   NOCONSTLIBBASE option.  Specifying CONSTLIBBASE allows the compiler to
   prevent extra register loading when making a series of calls to library
   functions through an external variable containing the library base.
@EndNode

@Node "COVERage"
COVER=COVERage/S			Default: nocover

Description

   This option tells the compiler to generate code to collect coverage
   analysis information.  Coverage analysis information allows you to
   determine which lines of your program have been executed by your test
   cases.

   If you specify the COVER option, make sure that you:

	· Link with the file LIB:covutil.o.
	· Do not specify the @{" NOSTDIO " Link "STDIO"} option.
	· Use @{" STARTUP " Link "STARTUP"}=C to link with the standard c.o startup module.

See Also

   @{" STARTUP " Link "STARTUP"} , @{" STDIO " Link "STDIO"}
@EndNode

@Node "CPU"
CPU/K					Default: any

Description

   This option generates code specific to the specified processor.  You
   can specify ANY, A, or 68000 to generate code for any processor.  You
   can also specify 68010, 68020, 68030, or 68040 to generate code for a
   specific processor.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   This option defines one or more preprocessor symbols.

   This option affects code generated by both the compiler and the
   assembler.
@EndNode

@Node "CSouRCe"
CSRC=CSouRCe/K

Description

   This option specifies C source files that are to be compiled and, if
   you specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option, linked into the program.

   This option does not have a negative form.

See Also

   @{" ASseMbler " Link "ASseMbler"} , @{" LIBrary " Link "LIBraries"} , @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" OBJect " Link "OBJects"}
@EndNode

@Node "DATA"
DATA/K					Default: near

Description

   This option specifies whether you want the compiler to generate 16-bit
   or 32-bit references to external and static data items.  You can
   specify any of the following:

	NEAR or N tells the compiler to use 16-bit references.

	FAR or F tells the compiler to use 32-bit references.  Register A4
	is still reserved to point to the near data section so that you
	can mix code compiled with DATA=NEAR and DATA=FAR.

	FARONLY or FO tells the compiler that your program never uses near
	data.  Register A4 is not reserved, therefore you cannot mix code
	compiled with DATA=NEAR.

	AUTO or A indicates that the first 64k of external data should
	generate 16-bit references and the remaining external data should
	generate 32-bit references.

   You can override this option on individual data items by using the
   __near, __far, or __chip keywords.

See Also

   @{" CODE " Link "CODE"}
@EndNode

@Node "DATAMEM"
@Title "DATAMEMory"
DATAMEM=DATAMEMory/K			Default: any

Description

   This option specifies the type of memory into which initialized static
   or external data should be loaded.  You can specify ANY, CHIP, or
   FAST.  You can abbreviate these values as A, C, or F.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   This option affects code generated by both the compiler and the
   assembler.

See Also

   @{" BSSMEMory " Link "BSSMEM"} , @{" CODEMEMory " Link "CODEMEM"}
@EndNode

@Node "DATANAME"
DATANAME/K				Default: "data"

Description

   This option names the initialized data section.  You can specify
   DATANAME=NONE or NODATANAME if you want an unnamed data section.
   The linker automatically merges all sections with the same name.

See Also

   @{" BSSNAME " Link "BSSNAME"} , @{" CODENAME " Link "CODENAME"}
@EndNode

@Node "DeBuG"
DBG=DeBuG/K				Default: nodbg

Description

   This option sets the debugging level of the compiler.  If you do not
   want the compiler to generate debugging information, specify NODEBUG.
   To generate debugging information, specify DEBUG=LEVEL, where LEVEL is
   one of the following:

	LINE or L produces line number information only.

	SYMBOL or S produces line number information, information on
	automatic and formal variables, and information on external and
	static symbols that are referenced in the module being compiled.

	SYMBOLFLUSH or SF produces the same information as SYMBOL, and
	flushes any non-register variables being held in registers to
	memory at each line boundary to allow the debugger to accurately
	display their values in C source mode.

	FULL or F produces the same information as SYMBOL.  However,
	DEBUG=FULL produces information on all symbols whether or not the
	module references the symbol.

	FULLFLUSH or FF produces the same information as FULL, and flushes
	any non-register variables being held in registers to memory at
	each line boundary to allow the debugger to accurately display
	their values in C source mode.

   Any debug option except NODEBUG adds the -d assembler option to any
   assembled files to force debugging line number information on assembler
   output.  Also, if you specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option and any debug option
   except NODEBUG, the @{" ADDSYM " Link "ADDSYM"} option is passed to the linker.

See Also

   @{" ADDSYM " Link "ADDSYM"} , @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "DEFine"
DEF=DEFINE/K

   This option defines the specified preprocessor symbol, as if with a
   #define statement.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Do not enter a space between the symbol name and the following equal
   sign.  If the value contains a space, enclose the entire argument in
   double quotes (").

   Any symbols defined with the DEFINE option are defined in the assembler
   as well.

   NOTE:  The DEFINE compiler option does not affect the linker.  Do not
   confuse this option with the DEFINE linker option.
@EndNode

@Node "DISASseM"
@Title "DISASseMble"
DISASM=DISASseMble/K			Default: nodisasm

Description

   This option tells the compiler to disassemble the code as it is
   generated and to send the disassembly to the file you specify.

   To send the disassembly to the Shell, use DISASM=*.
@EndNode

@Node "ERRor"
ERR=ERRor/K/N

Description

   This option tells the compiler to treat the specified message as an
   error.  You can specify ALL or A to promote all enabled warnings to
   errors, or you can specify one or more message numbers to promote only
   those messages.

   This option does not have a negative form.

See Also

   @{" IGNore " Link "IGNore"} , @{" WaRN " Link "WaRN"}
@EndNode

@Node "ERRorCONsole"
ERRCON=ERRorCONsole/S			Default: errcon

Description

   This option enables printing of diagnostics to the console (stdout).

See Also

   @{" ERRorHIGHlight " Link "ERRorHIGHlight"} , @{" ERRorLIST " Link "ERRorLISTing"} , @{" ERRorREXX " Link "ERRorREXX"} , @{" ERRorSouRCe " Link "ERRorSouRCe"}
@EndNode

@Node "ERRorHIGHlight"
ERRHIGH=ERRorHIGHlight/S		Default: errhigh

Description

   This option highlights the token that caused the error using @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"}
   escape sequences in diagnostic output that is sent to the console.

See Also

   @{" ERRorCONsole " Link "ERRorCONsole"} , @{" ERRorLIST " Link "ERRorLISTing"} , @{" ERRorREXX " Link "ERRorREXX"} , @{" ERRorSouRCe " Link "ERRorSouRCe"}
@EndNode

@Node "ERRorLISTing"
@Title "ERRorLIST"
ERRLIST=ERRorLIST/S			Default: errlist

Description

   This option prints diagnostic messages to the listing file.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the LIST option.

See Also

   @{" ERRorCONsole " Link "ERRorCONsole"} , @{" ERRorHIGHlight " Link "ERRorHIGHlight"} , @{" ERRorREXX " Link "ERRorREXX"} , @{" ERRorSouRCe " Link "ERRorSouRCe"}
@EndNode

@Node "ERRorREXX"
ERRREXX=ERRorREXX/S			Default: noerrrexx

Description

   This option sends diagnostic messages to the SCMSG utility.

See Also

   @{" ERRorCONsole " Link "ERRorCONsole"} , @{" ERRorHIGHlight " Link "ERRorHIGHlight"} , @{" ERRorLIST " Link "ERRorLISTing"} , @{" ERRorSouRCe " Link "ERRorSouRCe"}
@EndNode

@Node "ERRorSouRCe"
ERRSRC=ERRorSouRCe/S			Default: errsrc

   This option prints lines from the C source file with the diagnostic
   messages that are sent to the console.

See Also

   @{" ERRorCONsole " Link "ERRorCONsole"} , @{" ERRorHIGHlight " Link "ERRorHIGHlight"} , @{" ERRorLIST " Link "ERRorLISTing"} , @{" ERRorREXX " Link "ERRorREXX"}
@EndNode

@Node "EXTernalDEFs"
EXTDEF=EXTernalDEFs/S			Default: extdef

Description

   This option treats all external declaration as definitions.
@EndNode

@Node "FindSYMbol"
FSYM=FindSYMbol/K

Description

   This option tells the compiler to print a warning message each time the
   specified symbol is defined.

   This option does not have a negative form.
@EndNode

@Node "FROM"
FROM/S

Description

   This option is included only for compatibility with the SLINK command.

   The compiler ignores this option.

   This option does not have a negative form.
@EndNode

@Node "GenProtoDATAitems"
GPDATA=GenProtoDATAitems/S		Default: gpdata

Description

   This option generates external declarations for variables defined in
   the source files that are not defined as STATIC.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"} option.

See Also

   @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"}
@EndNode

@Node "GenProtoEXTerns"
GPEXT=GenProtoEXTerns/S 		Default: gpext

Description

   This option generates prototypes for externally-known routines.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"} option.

See Also

   @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"}
@EndNode

@Node "GenProtoFILE"
GPFILE=GenProtoFILE/K			Default: <filename>_protos.h

Description

   This option specifies the name of the file in which to place the
   generated prototypes.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"} option.

See Also

   @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"}
@EndNode

@Node "GenProtoPARMs"
@Title "GenProtoPARaMeters"
GPPARM=GenProtoPARaMeters/S		Default: nogpparm

Description

   This option generates prototypes using the __PARMS macro.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"} option.

See Also

   @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"}
@EndNode

@Node "GenPROTO"
@Title "GenPROTOs"
GPROTO=GenPROTOs/S			Default: nogproto

Description

   This option generates prototypes and data declarations instead of
   compiling your file.

See Also

   @{" GenProtoDATAitems " Link "GenProtoDATAitems"} , @{" GenProtoEXTerns " Link "GenProtoEXTerns"} , @{" GenProtoFILE " Link "GenProtoFILE"} ,
   @{" GenProtoPARaMeters " Link "GenProtoPARMs"} , @{" GenProtoSTATics " Link "GenProtoSTATics"} , @{" GenProtoTypeDEFs " Link "GenProtoTypeDEFs"}
@EndNode

@Node "GenProtoSTATics"
GPSTAT=GenProtoSTATics/S		Default: nogpstat

Description

   This option generates prototypes for static routines.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"} option.

See Also

   @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"}
@EndNode

@Node "GenProtoTypeDEFs"
GPTDEF=GenProtoTypeDEFs/S		Default: gptdef

Description

   This option tells the compiler to use typedefs instead of resolved
   types when generating prototypes for any functions using typedefs for
   parameters or return values.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"} option.

See Also

   @{" GenPROTOs " Link "GenPROTO"}
@EndNode

@Node "GST"
@Title "GlobalSymbolTable"
GST=GlobalSymbolTable/K 		Default: nogst

Description

   This option tells the compiler to use the specified GST (Global Symbol
   Table).

   The GST must have been created using the @{" MakeGlobalSymbolTable " Link "MakeGST"} option
   during a previous compilation.

   The GST option is ignored if you specify the @{" MakeGlobalSymbolTable " Link "MakeGST"}
   option.

See Also

   @{" MakeGlobalSymbolTable " Link "MakeGST"}
@EndNode

@Node "GSTIMMediate"
GSTIMM=GSTIMMediate/S			Default: nogstimm

Description

   This option is included for compatibility with projects using
   precompiled header files as implemented in Version 5 of the compiler.
   This option makes the contents of the GST you specify with the @{" GST " Link "GST"}
   option immediately available to the program.

See Also

   @{" GlobalSymbolTable " Link "GST"} , @{" MakeGlobalSymbolTable " Link "MakeGST"}
@EndNode

@Node "ICONs"
ICON=ICONs/S				Default: icon

Description

   This option tells the compiler to create icons for files that it
   creates, including listing files, preprocessor output files, prototype
   files, and object files.

   If you specify NOICONS and @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}, the NOICONS option is also passed to
   the linker.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "IDentifierLENgth"
IDLEN=IDentifierLENgth/K/N		Default: 255

Description

   This option specifies the maximum number of significant characters in
   an identifier.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Identifiers longer than the max are truncated without warning.

   Identifiers longer than IDLEN bytes that differ after the first IDLEN
   bytes are treated as identical.
@EndNode

@Node "IGNore"
IGN=IGNore/K/N

Description

   This option tells the compiler to ignore the specified warning message.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   You cannot ignore error messages.

   You can specify ALL or A to ignore all warning messages, or you can
   specify one or more message numbers to ignore only those messages.

See Also

   @{" ERRor " Link "ERRor"} , @{" WaRN " Link "WaRN"}
@EndNode

@Node "IncludeDIRectory"
IDIR=IncludeDIRectory/K 		Default: <current dir>, Include:

Description

   This option adds a directory to the list of directories to search for
   include files.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Any directories you specify with INCLUDEDIRECTORY are also passed to
   the assembler as header file search directories.
@EndNode

@Node "KeepLINE"
KLINE=KeepLINE/S			Default: nokline

   This option generates #line directives in the preprocessor output file
   that correspond to the lines in the original source files.

   This option allows you to compile the preprocessed source and get error
   and warning messages that refer you to the correct line in the
   nonpreprocessed version of the file.  This option is ignored if you do
   not specify the @{" PPONLY " Link "PreProcessONLY"} option.

See Also

   @{" PreProcessorONLY " Link "PreProcessONLY"}
@EndNode

@Node "LIBCODE"
LIBCODE/S				Default: nolibcode

Description

   This option tells the compiler that the compiled code will be linked
   into a shared library.  Any functions compiled with LIBCODE and either
   the __saveds keyword or the @{" SAVEDS " Link "SAVEDS"} option load their near data
   section from a point relative to the library base register A6 instead
   of from a global data area.	LIBCODE also guarantees that the current
   library base will be in register A6 whenever A6 is referenced or an
   internal call is made.

   Do not use this option when creating a normal executable module.

See Also

   @{" SAVEDS " Link "SAVEDS"}
@EndNode

@Node "LIBraries"
@Title "LIBrary"
LIB=LIBrary/K

Description

   This option specifies the link libraries that are to be passed to the
   linker.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Any libraries you specify are passed to the linker before the SAS/C
   libraries.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" ASseMbler " Link "ASseMbler"} , @{" CSouRCe " Link "CSouRCe"} , @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" OBJect " Link "OBJects"}
@EndNode

@Node "LINK"
LINK/S					Default: nolink

Description

   This option tells the compiler to invoke the linker to produce a final
   executable.

   If you do not specify LINK, the compiler ignores any object files and
   link libraries that you specify.

   The options passed to the linker are placed into the file
   <program>.lnk, and the linker is invoked using this file as a WITH
   file.

   To see which linker options were generated, look at the .lnk file after
   sc runs the linker.

See Also

   @{" LINKerOPTions " Link "LINKerOPTs"}
@EndNode

@Node "LINKerOPTs"
@Title "LINKerOPTions"
LINKOPT=LINKerOPTions/K 		Default: nolinkopt

Description

   This option passes the provided parameter to the linker as command line
   options.

   If you want to specify more than one option, or if the option you want
   to specify contains a blank, surround the entire option string with
   double quotes (").

   Any options specified in the options string are passed to the linker
   after any compiler options that are identified as valid only if you
   specify @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}.  Therefore, the LINKEROPTIONS values override the
   values passed by the SC options.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "LIST"
LIST/S					Default: nolist

Description

   This option tells the compiler or assembler to produce a listing file.

   The compiler writes the output to the filename you specify with the
   @{" ListFILE " Link "ListFILE"} option.  If you do not specify an output filename, the
   compiler uses the name of the first source file you specify but with
   the extension .lst.

See Also

   @{" ListFILE " Link "ListFILE"} , @{" ListHEADers " Link "ListHEADers"} , @{" ListINCludes " Link "ListINCludes"} ,
   @{" ListMACros " Link "ListMACros"} , @{" ListNARRow " Link "ListNARRow"} , @{" ListSYStem " Link "ListSYStem"}
@EndNode

@Node "ListFILE"
LFILE=ListFILE/K			Default: <first filename>.lst

Description

   This option names the listing and/or cross reference file.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} or @{" XREFerence " Link "XREF"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} , @{" XREFerence " Link "XREF"}
@EndNode

@Node "ListHEADers"
LHEAD=ListHEADers/S			Default: lhead

Description

   This option tells the compiler or assembler to include user header
   files in the listing.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} option.

See Also

   @{" LIST " Link "LIST"}
@EndNode

@Node "ListINCludes"
LINC=ListINCludes/S			Default: linc

Description

   This option lists the names of all included .h files in the listing
   file.

   This option is useful for determining:

	· .h file dependencies for SMAKE
	· the exact path of each .h file used
	· exactly which .h files are included by other .h files.

   The hierarchy of files is indicated by indention levels; a file
   included by another file is indented one level deeper than the parent
   file.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} option.

See Also

   @{" LIST " Link "LIST"}
@EndNode

@Node "ListMACros"
LMAC=ListMACros/S			Default: nolmac

Description

   This option tells the compiler or assembler to expand macros in the
   listing.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} option.

See Also

   @{" LIST " Link "LIST"}
@EndNode

@Node "ListNARRow"
LNARR=ListNARRow/S			Default: lnarr

Description

   This option tells the compiler or assembler to produce a narrow listing
   (less than 80 columns wide).

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} option.

See Also

   @{" LIST " Link "LIST"}
@EndNode

@Node "ListSYStem"
LSYS=ListSYStem/S			Default: nolsys

Description

   This option tells the compiler to include system header files in the
   listing.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LIST " Link "LIST"} option.

See Also

   @{" LIST " Link "LIST"}
@EndNode

@Node "MakeGST"
@Title "MakeGlobalSymbolTable"
MGST=MakeGlobalSymbolTable/K

Description

   This option creates a GST (Global Symbol Table).

   If you specify the @{" GST " Link "GST"} and MAKEGST options, the @{" GST " Link "GST"} option is ignored.

   This option automatically enables the @{" NOMULTIPLEINCLUDES " Link "MultipleINCludes"} and
   @{" NOEXTERNALDEFS " Link "EXTernalDEFs"} options.

See Also

   @{" EXTernalDEFs " Link "EXTernalDEFs"} , @{" MultipleINCludes " Link "MultipleINCludes"}
@EndNode

@Node "MAP"
MAP/S					Default: nomap

Description

   This option produces a map of the executable module.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MapFILE " Link "MapFILE"} , @{" MapHUNK " Link "MapHUNK"} , @{" MapLIB " Link "MapLIBraries"} ,
   @{" MapOVerLaY " Link "MapOVerLaY"} , @{" MapSYMbols " Link "MapSYMbols"} , @{" MapXREFerence " Link "MapXREF"}
@EndNode

@Node "MapFILE"
MFILE=MapFILE/K 			Default: <executable name>.map

Description

   This option names the map file.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify both the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} and @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
@EndNode

@Node "MapHUNK"
MHUNK=MapHUNK/S 			Default: nomhunk

Description

   This option maps all output hunks by size and originating function.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify both the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} and @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
@EndNode

@Node "MapLIBraries"
@Title "MapLIB"
MLIB=MapLIB/S				Default: nomlib

Description

   This option generates a list of hunks by library symbol in the map.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} and @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
@EndNode

@Node "MapOVerLaY"
MOVLY=MapOVerLaY/S			Default: nomovly

Description

   This option includes a list of hunks in each overlay in the map.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} and @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
@EndNode

@Node "MapSYMbols"
MSYM=MapSYMbols/S			Default: nomsym

Description

   This option includes a list of defined symbols and the location at
   which they are defined.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} and @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
@EndNode

@Node "MapXREF"
@Title "MapXREFerence"
MXREF=MapXREFerence/S			Default: nomxref

Description

   This option writes a symbol cross-reference to the map file that lists
   each symbol definition and the places each symbol is used.

   This option can generate a lot of output, but it is useful when you are
   trying to track down where an unresolved symbol is referenced.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} and @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
   options.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} , @{" MAP " Link "MAP"}
@EndNode

@Node "MATH"
MATH/K					Default: nomath

Description

   This option chooses a format for floating-point math and, if you also
   specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option, links with the appropriate math library.

   You can specify one of the following as the type:

	STANDARD or S links with the library scm.lib (or with scms.lib if
	you specify the SHORTINT option).  The math format is IEEE.

	FFP or F generates code to call the FFP shared library provided by
	Commodore.  The math format is FFP.

	68881, 68882, or 8 generates inline code for the 68881 and 68882
	coprocessors.  If you specify one of these coprocessor options,
	your program will not run if a coprocessor is not available.
	COPROCESSOR is a synonym for these options.  The math format is
	IEEE.

	IEEE or I generates code to call the IEEE shared library provided
	by Commodore.  The math format is IEEE.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "MAXERRor"
@Title "MAXimumERRors"
MAXERR=MAXimumERRors/K/N		Default: 50

Description

   This option sets the limit on the number of errors for a single
   compilation.

   If a single compilation generates more than MAXERR errors, the compiler
   aborts the compilation.  NOMAXERR removes any limits.

See Also

   @{" MAXimumWaRNings " Link "MAXWaRN"}
@EndNode

@Node "MAXWaRN"
@Title "MAXimumWaRNings"
MAXWRN=MAXimumWaRNings/K/N		Default: nomaxwrn

Description

   This option sets the limit on the number of warnings for a single
   compilation.

   If a single compilation generates more than MAXWRN warnings, the
   compiler aborts the compilation.  NOMAXWRN removes any limits.

See Also

   @{" MAXimumERRors " Link "MAXERRor"}
@EndNode

@Node "MEMSIZE"
@Title "MEMorySIZE"
MEMSIZE=MEMorySIZE/K			Default: large

Description

   This option tells the compiler approximately how much memory you have
   on your system.  You can specify one of the following:

	TINY   or T
	SMALL  or S
	MEDIUM or M
	LARGE  or L
	HUGE   or H

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Larger sizes allow SC to compile more complex programs and to compile
   faster.  Smaller sizes allow SC to continue to work under low-memory
   conditions.	If the compiler runs out of memory during a compilation,
   it displays the message "***Freeing Resources", attempts to free up
   memory, and automatically drops to a lower MEMORYSIZE value.

   MEMORYSIZE affects how and where the compiler stores any debugging
   information.  If the compiler begins to run out of memory, it starts
   writing debugging information to a disk file.  This file is referred to
   as a "debug side file".

   MEMORYSIZE also affects the disposition and buffering of the compiler
   intermediate file.  This option tells the compiler how much initial
   memory space to reserve for the intermediate information.  For LARGE
   and HUGE, the intermediate file is kept totally in memory, which is
   much faster than writing it to disk when the memory is available.  At
   smaller values, the intermediate file is written to disk, but the
   MEMORYSIZE value affects the amount that is buffered.

   In addition, if you do not specify the @{" PreProcessorBUFfer " Link "PreProcessorBUFfer"} and/or
   @{" ARGumentSIZe " Link "ARGumentSIZe"} options, the MEMSIZE option sets these values for you.
   If you specify the @{" PreProcessorBUFfer " Link "PreProcessorBUFfer"} and/or @{" ARGumentSIZe " Link "ARGumentSIZe"} options, the
   values you specify override the values set by MEMORYSIZE.

   The following table lists the default values for @{" ARGumentSIZe " Link "ARGumentSIZe"} and
   @{" PreProcessorBUFfer " Link "PreProcessorBUFfer"} set by MEMORYSIZE.  It also lists the buffer size
   and location of the compiler intermediate file.

				Intermediate	Debug Side
	memsize argsize ppbuf	File Buffer	File Buffer

	TINY	  127	 1024	    1024	     2K
	SMALL	  255	 2048	    4096	     8K
	MEDIUM	  511	 4096	    8192	    32K
	LARGE	 1023	 8192	  no limit	    64K
	HUGE	 4800	16384	  no limit	   128K

See Also

   @{" ARGumentSIZe " Link "ARGumentSIZe"} , @{" PreProcessorBUFfer " Link "PreProcessorBUFfer"}
@EndNode

@Node "MODified"
MOD=MODified/S				Default: nomod

Description

   This option tells the SC command to process only files that are out of
   date with respect to their output files.

   This option is useful if you are compiling several files with a single
   SC command and only some of the files need to be recompiled.

   This option also works when you are generating prototypes or
   preprocessor output.

   If you also specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option, all object files are included in
   the link, even if their source files were not recompiled.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "MultipleCharacterCONStants"
MCCONS=MultipleCharacterCONStants/K	Default: nomccons

Description

   This option allows up to four bytes to appear within single quotes as a
   character constant.

   This option is included only for compatibility with previous releases
   of the compiler, and its use is not recommended.

   If you specify MCCONS, a single constant of type int is generated.  If
   fewer than four bytes are provided, they are padded on the left with
   zeroes.
@EndNode

@Node "MultipleINCludes"
MINC=MultipleINCludes/S 		Default: minc

Description

   This option tells the compiler to include header files that are
   included more than once.

   This behavior is required by the @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} Standard.  However, many projects
   do not need this behavior, and specifying NOMINC can save compilation
   time.

See Also

   @{" ANSI Definition " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"}
@EndNode

@Node "OBJects"
@Title "OBJect"
OBJ=OBJect/K

Description

   This option lists the object files that are to be linked into the
   program.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   The object files must have been created during a previous compilation.

   Do not specify object files that will be created by the same SC command
   in which you specify the OBJECT option.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" ASseMbler " Link "ASseMbler"} , @{" CSouRCe " Link "CSouRCe"} , @{" LIBrary " Link "LIBraries"}
@EndNode

@Node "OBJectLIB"
@Title "OBJectLIBrary"
OBJLIB=OBJectLIBrary/K

Description

   This option specifies that any resulting object files are to be placed
   in the named link library.

   Do not specify this option if you also specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "OBJectNAME"
OBJNAME=OBJectNAME/K

Description

   This option specifies the name of the file or directory to hold
   compiler and assembler output.

   If you are compiling or assembling only one C source file or
   assembly-language file, you can use this option to specify the file
   where you want the compiler or assembler output.

   If you are compiling or assembling more than one file, you can use this
   option to specify a directory where you want the output, and SC uses
   the same filename as the source file but replaces the extension with
   ".o".

   The directory name must end with a forward slash (/) or a colon (:).

   If you do not use the OBJECTNAME option, SC uses the same filename with
   the extension of ".o", and it places the files in the same directory as
   the source file.
@EndNode

@Node "OLDPreProcessor"
OLDPP=OLDPreProcessor/S 		Default: nooldpp

Description

   This option is provided for compatibility with pre-@{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} style
   preprocessors.

   The OLDPP option does the following:

	· allows old-style token pasting using comments
	· substitutes values for parameters specified as quoted strings in
	  macro definitions.

See Also

   @{" ANSI Definition " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"}
@EndNode

@Node "ONERRor"
ONERR=ONERRor/K 			Default: stop

Description

   This option tells SC what action to take if a C or assembly language
   source file generates an error.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   You can specify one of the following:

	STOP or S tells SC not to process any more source files.

	CONTINUE or C tells SC to process the next source file.

   If you specify the LINK option, but your program generates errors, your
   program is not linked even if you specify ONERR=CONTINUE.
@EndNode

@Node "OPTimize"
OPT=OPTimize/S				Default: noopt

Description

   This option enables the global optimizer (unless you specify
   NOOPTGLOBAL) and peephole optimizer (unless you specify NOOPTPEEP).

See Also

   @{" OPTimizerALIAS " Link "OPTALIAS"} , @{" OPTimizerCOMPlexity " Link "OPTCOMP"} , @{" OPTimizerDEPth " Link "OPTDEPth"} ,
   @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} , @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} , @{" OPTimizerINLOCAL " Link "OPTINLOCAL"} ,
   @{" OPTimizerLOOP " Link "OPTLOOP"} , @{" OPTimizerPEEPhole " Link "OPTimizePEEP"} , @{" OPTimizerRecurDEPth " Link "OPTRDEPth"} ,
   @{" OPTimizerSIZE " Link "OPTSIZE"} , @{" OPTimizerTIME " Link "OPTTIME"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTALIAS"
@Title "OPTimizerALIAS"
OPTALIAS=OPTimizerALIAS/S		Default: nooptalias

Description

   This option disables type-based aliasing assumptions in the optimizer.

   If you specify OPTIMIZERALIAS, the global optimizer uses worst-case
   aliasing.  Specifying OPTIMIZERALIAS can significantly reduce the
   amount of optimization that can be performed.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} option, or
   you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTCOMP"
@Title "OPTimizerCOMPlexity"
OPTCOMP=OPTimizerCOMPlexity/K/N 	Default: 3

Description

   This option defines the maximum complexity level of functions to be
   automatically inlined.

   The parameter represents the relative complexity of the function to be
   inlined and is a count of the number of discrete operations in the
   function.

   Try different values for this number until you get the results you
   want.

   Specify a value of 3 or higher.

   The higher the number, the more functions you can inline, but the size
   of your code will grow significantly as well.

   If you specify NOOPTCOMP, no complexity-based inlining occurs.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} and
   @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} options, or you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTDEPth"
@Title "OPTimizerDEPth"
OPTDEP=OPTimizerDEPth/K/N		Default: 3

Description

   This option defines the maximum nesting depth of automatically inlined
   functions.

   Specify a value of 3 or higher.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} and
   @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} options, or you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTimizeGlObal"
@Title "OPTimizerGlObal"
OPTGO=OPTimizerGlObal/S 		Default: optgo

Description

   This option enables the global optimizer.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the OPTimize option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTINLine"
@Title "OPTimizerINLine"
OPTINL=OPTimizerINLine/S		Default: optinl

Description

   This option allows inlining of functions, including functions defined
   with the __inline keyword.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} option, or
   you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

   If you do not specify this option, the @{" OPTINLOCAL " Link "OPTINLOCAL"}, @{" OPTDEPth " Link "OPTDEPth"},
   @{" OPTCOMPlexity, " Link "OPTCOMP"} and @{" OPTRDEPth " Link "OPTRDEPth"} options are ignored.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerCOMPlexity " Link "OPTCOMP"} , @{" OPTimizerDEPth " Link "OPTDEPth"} ,
   @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} , @{" OPTimizerINLOCAL " Link "OPTINLOCAL"} , @{" OPTimizerRecurDEPth " Link "OPTRDEPth"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTINLOCAL"
@Title "OPTimizerINLOCAL"
OPTINLOCAL=OPTimizerINLOCAL/S		Default: nooptinlocal

Description

   This option inlines single-use static functions.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} and
   @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} options or if you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTLOOP"
@Title "OPTimizerLOOP"
OPTLOOP=OPTimizerLOOP/S 		Default: optloop

Description

   This option enables loop optimizations.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} option, or
   you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTimizePEEP"
@Title "OPTimizerPEEPhole"
OPTPEEP=OPTimizerPEEPhole/S		Default: optpeep

Description

   This option enables the peephole optimizer.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTRDEPth"
@Title "OPTimizerRecurDEPth"
OPTRDEP=OPTimizerRecurDEPth/K/N 	Default: 3

Description

   This option defines the maximum depth of recursion of automatically
   inlined functions.

   Specify a value of 3 or higher.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} and
   @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} options, or you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerINLine " Link "OPTINLine"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTSIZE"
@Title "OPTimizerSIZE"
OPTSIZE=OPTimizerSIZE/S 		Default: nooptsize

Description

   This option disables optimizations that may sacrifice code size to save
   time.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} option, or
   you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

   Do not specify both the OPTimizerSIZE and @{" OPTimizerTIME " Link "OPTTIME"} options.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} , @{" OPTimizerTIME " Link "OPTTIME"}
@EndNode

@Node "OPTTIME"
@Title "OPTimizerTIME"
OPTTIME=OPTimizerTIME/S 		Default: noopttime

Description

   This option disables optimizations that may sacrifice time to save
   space.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} option, or
   you specify the @{" NOOPTGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} option.

   Do not specify both the @{" OPTimizerSIZE " Link "OPTSIZE"} and OPTimizerTIME options.

See Also

   @{" OPTimize " Link "OPTimize"} , @{" OPTimizerGlObal " Link "OPTimizeGlObal"} , @{" OPTimizerSIZE " Link "OPTSIZE"}
@EndNode

@Node "PARMs"
@Title "PARaMeters"
PARM=PARaMeters/K			Default: stack

Description

   This option indicates how parameters should be passed.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   You can specify one of the following:

	STACK or S indicates parameters should be passed on the stack.

	REGISTER or R indicates parameters should be passed in registers.

	BOTH or B generates a combination prolog that allows parameters to
	be passed on the stack or in registers.

   If your program has prototypes for all routines, you should use
   PARAMETERS=REGISTER for increased efficiency.

   If you are placing code into a link library, specify PARMS=BOTH so that
   your library functions accept registerized parameters and parameters
   that are passed on the stack.

   If you write a function that has the same name as a library function,
   you need to add the __regargs keyword to your function or compile with
   the PARMS=BOTH or PARMS=REGISTER option.
@EndNode

@Node "PRECision"
PREC=PRECision/K			Default: mixed

Description

   This option specifies the size of floating-point variables.	You can
   specify DOUBLE or MIXED.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   If you specify DOUBLE, data declared as FLOAT are treated as if they
   were declared as DOUBLE.  If you specify MIXED, data declared as
   FLOAT and data declared as DOUBLE are different sizes.
@EndNode

@Node "PreProcessorBUFfer"
PPBUF=PreProcessorBUFfer/K/N		Default: 8192

Description

   This option sets the maximum number of bytes to which a macro can be
   expanded by the preprocessor.

   The default value can be set differently by the @{" MEMorySIZE " Link "MEMSIZE"} option.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   If a macro expands to greater than PPBUF bytes, the compiler issues an
   error message and aborts the compilation.

See Also

   @{" MEMorySIZE " Link "MEMSIZE"}
@EndNode

@Node "PreProcessONLY"
@Title "PreProcessorONLY"
PPONLY=PreProcessorONLY/S		Default: nopponly

Description

   This option tells the compiler to run only the preprocessor on the C
   source files.

   If you specify a filename with the @{" OBJectNAME " Link "OBJectNAME"} option, the compiler
   writes the output to the file you specify.

   If you do not specify an output filename, the compiler writes the
   output to the same filename as the source file but with the extension
   ".p".

See Also

   @{" OBJectNAME " Link "OBJectNAME"}
@EndNode

@Node "ProgramNAME"
PNAME=ProgramNAME/K			Default: <root of first file>

Description

   This option specifies the name of the executable module.

   The default value is the root name of the first source file specified
   in the SC command.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "RESetOPTions"
RESOPT=RESetOPTions/S

Description

   This option resets all options to their default values.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   If you specify this option as the first option in the SC command, it
   resets any option specified in the SCOPTIONS file.  If you specify this
   option after other options or filenames in the SC command, it resets
   the options preceding it, including the filenames.
@EndNode

@Node "SAVEDS"
SAVEDS/S				Default: nosaveds

Description

   This option generates code as if you had defined all functions in the
   source files with the __saveds keyword.

   The __saveds keyword restores the near data pointer in register A4 at
   each function entry point.  You should specify this option if you are
   compiling code that is used as an interrupt routine, called with the
   AddTask() function, used in a shared library, or called from another
   process.

   This option does not work if your code is linked with the cres.o or
   catchres.o startup modules.
@EndNode

@Node "ShortINTegers"
SINT=ShortINTegers/S			Default: nosint

Description

   This option enables 16-bit integers.

   If you specify SHORTINTEGERS, types int and short are the same size.

   If you specify NOSHORTINTEGERS, types int and long are the same size.

   If you are running the assembler, this option defines the symbol
   shortint.
@EndNode

@Node "SmallCODE"
SCODE=SmallCODE/S			Default: noscode

Description

   This option tells the linker to merge all CODE hunks into a single
   hunk.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "SmallDATA"
SDATA=SmallDATA/S			Default: nosdata

Description

   This option tells the linker to merge all DATA and BSS sections into a
   single hunk.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "SouRCeIS"
SRCIS=SouRCeIS/K

Description

   This option sets the name of the C source file in the object file and
   in debugging information to the specified value instead of the actual
   name of the C source file.

   You can use this option if you plan to rename or move the source file
   before using the debugger to debug your program.

   If you are compiling or assembling exactly one source file, SOURCEIS
   can specify the name of the file to be placed into the debug
   information.

   If you are compiling or assembling multiple files, SOURCEIS should
   specify a directory name (ending with a forward slash or colon).
@EndNode

@Node "STacKCHecK"
STKCHK=STacKCHecK/S			Default: stkchk

Description

   This option generates stack overflow checking code at each function
   entry.

   When a program is about to run out of stack space, the program displays
   a requestor and terminates gracefully.

See Also

   @{" STacKEXtend " Link "STacKEXTend"}
@EndNode

@Node "STacKEXTend"
STKEXT=STacKEXTend/S			Default: nostkext

Description

   This option generates stack extension code at each function entry.

   When a program runs out of space in the current stack, a new stack is
   allocated, and your program continues to run.

See Also

   @{" STacKCHecK " Link "STacKCHecK"}
@EndNode

@Node "STDIO"
@Title "STanDardIO"
STDIO=STanDardIO/S			Default: stdio

Description

   This option specifies the use of __main instead of __tinymain.

   To use __tinymain, specify NOSTDIO.

   Using __tinymain makes your program require less space, but you cannot
   read from or send output to stdin, stdout, or stderr.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "STaRTup"
STRT=STaRTup/K				Default: c (for c.o)

Description

   This option specifies which startup module to use.

   If the module name that you specify does not contain a colon (:),
   forward slash (/), or period (.), the compiler adds "lib:" to the
   beginning and ".o" to the end of the name you specify.

   If you do not want to compile with a startup module, specify
   NOSTARTUP.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "STRICT"
STRICT/S				Default: nostrict

Description

   This option enables a large number of diagnostics dealing with
   portability and questionable situations in your code.

   Specifying STRICT may produce warning messages for situations that are
   not a problem.
@EndNode

@Node "STRingMERge"
STRMER=STRingMERge/S			Default: nostrmer

Description

   This option merges all identical string constants in the C source file
   and places all strings, all data declared "static const", and all auto
   initializers in the CODE section instead of the DATA section.

   If you specify STRINGMERGE, the compiler examines each string constant
   defined in the code and checks for duplicates.  If the compiler finds a
   duplicate string constant, it forces both references to refer to the
   same memory location.

   If you specify STRINGMERGE and you modify a string constant, the
   constant is modified in all locations.

   The STRINGMERGE option has two useful side effects, because some data
   are placed in the code section:

	· Less data needs to be placed into the near data section.  If you
	  have more than 64k of data, you can use the STRINGMERGE option
	  to try to reduce the amount of data and allow your code to
	  continue to use the near data model.

	· The string constants are addressed relative to the PC (program
	  counter) instead of the beginning of the near data section.
	  Therefore, it is possible to generate programs with no near or
	  far data.
@EndNode

@Node "STRingsCONSt"
STRCONS=STRingsCONSt/S			Default: nostrcons

Description

   This option tells the compiler to consider all string constants to be
   of type "const char *".

   If you do not specify STRINGSCONST, the compiler considers string
   constants to be of type "char *".

   If you specify STRINGSCONST, passing a string constant to a function
   that expects the type "char *" generates a warning message indicating
   that the function may modify the string constant.
@EndNode

@Node "STRIPDeBuG"
STRIPDBG=STRIPDeBuG/S			Default: nostripdbg

Description

   This option strips all debugging information from the final executable.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" LINK " Link "LINK"} option.

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "STRuctEQuivalence"
@Title "STRuctureEQuivalence"
STREQ=STRuctureEQuivalence/S		Default: nostreq

Description

   This option tells the compiler not to issue messages if a pointer to
   one structure type is passed to a function when the function expects a
   pointer to a different type, if the type passed is equivalent to the
   type expected.
@EndNode

@Node "TO"
TO

Description

   This option is included only for compatibility with the SLINK command.
   TO is a synonym for the @{" ProgramNAME " Link "ProgramNAME"} option.

   This option does not have a negative form.

See Also

   @{" ProgramNAME " Link "ProgramNAME"}
@EndNode

@Node "TRIGraph"
TRIG=TRIGraph/S 			Default: notrig

Description

   This option specifies whether to use @{" ANSI " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"} trigraphs.

   Specifying TRIGRAPH slows down the compiler.

See Also

   @{" ANSI Definition " Link "sc:help/sc_lib.guide/Glossary - ANSI"}
@EndNode

@Node "UnderSCORE"
USCORE=UnderSCORE/S			Default: nouscore

Description

   This option adds underscores to the beginning of all external names
   defined in any assembler source files assembled.

   The underscores allow you to refer to these names in assembly language
   in the same way you do in C source files.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify any assembly-language
   files in the SC command.
@EndNode

@Node "UnsignedCHAR"
UCHAR=UnsignedCHAR/S			Default: nouchar

Description

   This option makes the default type of "char" variables unsigned
   instead of signed.
@EndNode

@Node "UTILLIB"
@Title "UTILityLIBrary"
UTILLIB=UTILityLIBrary/S		Default: noutillib

Description

   This option generates inline calls to the AmigaDOS 2.0 ROM-resident
   library utility.library to do integer multiplication and division
   instead of calling SAS/C library functions to do these operations.

   Specifying UTILITYLIBRARY makes your executable smaller and faster by
   taking advantage of 68020 instructions if they are available, but your
   program runs only under AmigaDOS 2.0.

   If you link using the SC command and the UTILITYLIBRARY and @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
   options, SC defines all the SAS/C library integer conversion stub
   routines to stubs that call utility.library.

   This action prevents the SAS/C library routines that use integer
   conversion routines from using the SAS/C versions of the routines.

   If you link using the SLINK command, you need to specify the following
   DEFINE linker options:

   define __CXM33=__UCXM33
   define __CXD33=__UCXD33
   define __CXM22=__UCXM22
   define __CXD22=__UCXD22

   These define options are in the file "LIB:utillib.with", so you can
   link with the following command:

	slink with LIB:utillib.with <options>

See Also

   @{" LINK " Link "LINK"}
@EndNode

@Node "VERBOSE"
VERBOSE 				Default: noverbose

Description

   This option displays messages about each stage of compiling and
   linking.
@EndNode

@Node "VERsion"
VER=VERsion/S				Default: ver

Description

   This option prints a banner containing the compiler version number and
   a copyright message.
@EndNode

@Node "WaRN"
WRN=WaRN/K/N

Description

   This option enables the specified compiler warning message.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   You can specify ALL or A to enable all warning messages, or you can
   specify one or more message numbers to enable only those messages.

See Also

   @{" ERRor " Link "ERRor"} , @{" IGNore " Link "IGNore"}
@EndNode

@Node "WarnVoidRETurn"
WVRET=WarnVoidRETurn/S			Default: wvret

Description

   This option issues a warning message if a function declared as
   returning an integer actually returns no value.

   The NOWARNVOIDRETURN option suppresses the "return value mismatch"
   warning message for functions declared as returning an integer, but
   that do not contain a return statement or that do not include an
   expression in the return statement.
@EndNode

@Node "WITH"
WITH/K

Description

   This option specifies the name of a file containing additional options.

   The additional options are read immediately, as if they were specified
   in the SC command at the position occupied by the WITH option.

   Options specified after the WITH option may override options specified
   in the with file.

   This option does not have a negative form.

   Do not confuse this option with the WITH linker option.
@EndNode

@Node "XREF"
@Title "XREFerence"
XREF=XREFerence/S			Default: noxref

Description

   This option produces a cross-reference.

   The compiler writes the output to the filename you specify with the
   @{" ListFILE " Link "ListFILE"} option.

   If you do not specify an output filename, the compiler uses the name of
   the first source file you specify but with the extension ".lst".

See Also

   @{" ListFILE " Link "ListFILE"} , @{" XreferenceHEADers " Link "XrefHEADers"} , @{" XreferenceSYStem " Link "XrefSYStem"}
@EndNode

@Node "XrefHEADers"
@Title "XreferenceHEADers"
XHEAD=XreferenceHEADers/S		Default: xhead

Description

   This option generates a cross-reference of user header files.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" XREFerence " Link "XREF"} option.

See Also

   @{" XREFerence " Link "XREF"}
@EndNode

@Node "XrefSYStem"
@Title "XreferenceSYStem"
XSYS=XreferenceSYStem/S 		Default: xsys

Description

   This option includes symbols defined in system header files in the
   cross-reference.

   This option is ignored if you do not specify the @{" XREFerence " Link "XREF"} option.

See Also

   @{" XREFerence " Link "XREF"}
@EndNode
@node HELP "HELP"
You have reached this Help window by either clicking on the Help
button or by hitting the Help key within the SAS/C Help utility.
Unlike other help topics present in the SAS/C Help utility, the Help
help topic opens its own window.  You must close this window by
clicking on the close gadget or hitting escape before returning to
the SAS/C help utility.  You cannot hit the Retrace button to return.

To quit the SAS/C Help utility, select Quit from the Project menu or
click on the close gadget.  You may also hit escape.

Most help screens will display one or more buttons as part of the text.
Clicking on these buttons will provide further information on the topic
listed on the button.  You can also reach these help topics through the
main Contents screen or one of its sub-screens.

In addition, double-clicking in the help window will bring up a help
screen for the word under the mouse cursor, if such a help screen
exists.

While in the SAS/C Help utility, you may retrace your steps through the
help screens you have selected by clicking on the Retrace button.

The Browse buttons will move you forward and backwards between help
screens.  The help screens are usually arranged alphabetically by
command or topic.
@endnode
